<div id="review_3829009087" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3829009087" />
    <a title="Linda ~ they got the mustard out! ~" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out"><img alt="Linda ~ they got the mustard out! ~" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1473475487p2/16915869.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3829009087?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda ~ they got the mustard out! ~" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda ~ they got the mustard out! ~" href="/user/show/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out">Linda ~ they got the mustard out! ~</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/13160258-an-echo-in-the-bone">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=3-and-a-half-stars">3-and-a-half-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=established-couple">established-couple</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=historical">historical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=animals-pets">animals-pets</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=action-adventure">action-adventure</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=medical-profession">medical-profession</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=read-in-2021">read-in-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16915869-linda-they-got-the-mustard-out?shelf=lgbtq-side-characters">lgbtq-side-characters</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3829009087" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15142165954532092734">3.5 stars <br/><br/>Now I remember why I didn&apos;t want to binge these last few books. But the show had to go and condense two books into one season, and are likely to do the same with books 7 &amp; 8, and I haven&apos;t read book 8 yet, so here we are.<br/><br/>At least with this one we&apos;ve finally reached the revolution, and we finally have an actual real plot and action in Outlander once again. Of course, this is Gabaldon, so we still have to spend time with all the other characters we don&apos;t care as much about (mainly Roger </span>
  <span id="freeText15142165954532092734" style="display:none">3.5 stars <br /><br />Now I remember why I didn't want to binge these last few books. But the show had to go and condense two books into one season, and are likely to do the same with books 7 &amp; 8, and I haven't read book 8 yet, so here we are.<br /><br />At least with this one we've finally reached the revolution, and we finally have an actual real plot and action in Outlander once again. Of course, this is Gabaldon, so we still have to spend time with all the other characters we don't care as much about (mainly Roger and Bree, who have nothing to do with anything but have to get page time anyway), and to a lesser degree William and Ian. There's a lot going on, and it should have moved the book right along, but I was just not as invested this time around, probably because I remembered all too clearly the idiocy that this book ended with and I was in no great hurry to get to it. <br /><br />And as always with these last few books, a ruthless editor was desperately in need, not just to cut this to a reasonable length but also to weed out all the inconsistencies within the text of this book and with previous ones. How is Ian both on a ship and running around upstate New York at the same time? How does Claire, a surgeon and doctor, not realize she needs glasses? How did Jamie forget that he saw Willie in the previous book, albeit from a distance? Why does Claire think she never heard John's side about the kiss he and Jamie shared? John told her about that in Voyager. In fact, that was the first time she heard the story. (And for the record, I absolutely hate the way Gabaldon decided to retcon that as Jamie testing John to appease her homophobic readers, because as it was written in Voyager, that kiss was sincere.) And as I mentioned before, the drama all over the end of this book. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Claire being suspected of sedition, and thus in danger from the British government again. So having to marry someone to save her from said government, again. In this case John. Since due to tragic miscommunication, they both think Jamie is dead since the boat he was supposed to be on had sunk. Although I'm not at all clear how marrying John would save her from being brought up on charges for sedition. But Gabaldon just really wanted Claire and John to boink for some twisted reason. Then Rachel and Ian fall for each other for ... reasons? And Jemmy being kidnapped and Cameron wanting to go back for the gold and I'm exhausted. And there's still more drama after that. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />But still, this is the revolution and that part is very well done and researched, as can be expected from this series. Sure, our characters just so happen to be important enough to run into and speak with some of the major players of the revolution, because you can't not include Washington, Jefferson, Franklin and even Benedict Arnold at one point or another in these books. The action was well done, and the scene when the fire started spreading through one of the encampments was one of the few scenes I remembered well even after eleven years. <br /><br />Still, after reading these last three books in too short a time, I'm in need of another break, so I'll hold off on diving into book 8 until closer to the next season airing, since I won't be watching as it airs anyway.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15142165954532092734" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


